mapped_rationale: The source term describes a benign atrioventricular (AV) conduction delay in which every atrial impulse is conducted to the ventricles but with a prolonged PR interval (> 200 ms). This definition precisely corresponds to first-degree AV block.  Target concept 314379 has the name “First degree atrioventricular block” and is defined as “a conduction disorder characterized by a uniformly prolonged PR interval (>200 ms) on ECG while all atrial impulses reach the ventricles.”   • Specificity is preserved (Rule 1): both the source and the target specify first-degree AV block, not just “AV block” in general.   • No over-specification is introduced (Rule 2): the target does not add extra details such as congenital, laterality, or degree beyond first-degree.   • Context validity (Rule 3): it is classified as a disorder of atrioventricular conduction, matching the clinical nature of the source term, and synonyms include “First degree heart block,” exactly mirroring the source phrase “AV block first degree.”  Therefore, concept 314379 is an exact clinical equivalent of the source term.

The source term describes any deviation from normal in any measured or observed parameter of cerebrospinal fluid—appearance, cell count, chemistry, microbiology, immunology, etc.—detected on lumbar-puncture specimens.   Concept 4065770, “Cerebrospinal fluid examination abnormal,” is defined as “a clinical finding indicating that one or more parameters measured during laboratory analysis of a CSF specimen fall outside established reference ranges.” This wording captures exactly the same breadth and intent: any abnormal result, of any type, arising from CSF analysis.  • Specificity preserved (Rule 1): The target is not broader than the source; both refer specifically to abnormal results in CSF, not to abnormalities in other body fluids or to any broader neurologic findings.   • No over-specification (Rule 2): The target does not introduce additional qualifiers (e.g., type of abnormality, severity, etiology) that are absent from the source term.   • Context appropriate (Rule 3): The concept resides under “Finding related to cerebrospinal fluid; Abnormal finding on evaluation procedure,” matching the clinical-finding nature of the source.   • Non-essential wording such as “examination” is acceptable because it conveys the same idea of an abnormal CSF finding; there is no conflicting qualifier.  All other candidate concepts are either too general (“Clinical finding”) or narrower (limited to immunologic, cytologic, microbiological, specific chemistry abnormalities, etc.), violating Rule 1. Therefore, concept 4065770 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Abnormal findings in cerebrospinal fluid, Abnormal histological findings
cleaned_term: Abnormal findings in cerebrospinal fluid, Abnormal histological findings
mapped_rationale: The source term describes “Any deviation from normal observed on microscopic (histologic) examination of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).” Thus the required concept must:  • Refer specifically to cerebrospinal fluid   • Represent a histological (microscopic structural) abnormality, not merely chemical, immunologic, cytologic or other types of findings.   • Contain no additional qualifiers (e.g., specific etiology, severity, or type of abnormality) that would over-specify the source term.  SNOMED concept 4172064 “Abnormal histological findings in CSF” satisfies all of these conditions:   1. It explicitly locates the abnormality in cerebrospinal fluid, matching the source location and maintaining specificity (Rule 1).   2. It is limited to histological abnormalities without adding extra clinical detail or subtype restrictions, so it is not more specific than the source (Rule 2).   3. Its definition (“Microscopic examination of cerebrospinal fluid reveals structural cellular or tissue abnormalities…”) matches the clinical meaning given in the source description, ensuring semantic equivalence (Rule 3).    Alternative candidates are either too broad (e.g., “Cerebrospinal fluid examination abnormal”), encompass different modalities (e.g., cytological, immunological, chemical findings) or lack the CSF specification (“Abnormal histology findings”). Therefore, concept 4172064 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Abnormal microbiological findings in specimens from male genital organs
target_concept_name: Abnormal microbiological finding in specimen from male genital organ
cleaned_term: Abnormal microbiological findings in specimens from male genital organs
mapped_concept_name: Abnormal microbiological finding in specimen from male genital organ
mapped_rationale: The source term describes “abnormal microbiological findings” (i.e., detection of pathogenic or atypical microorganisms) in “specimens from male genital organs.”   Concept 4171911 is defined as “Detection of pathogenic or atypical microorganisms in … a specimen taken from any male genital structure … indicating potential infection or abnormal colonization.”    This concept: • Maintains specificity: It is limited to microbiological findings (not cytology, histology, immunology) and explicitly pertains to specimens from male genital organs, matching the source term’s anatomic location and test type.   • Does not over-specify: It does not introduce narrower details (e.g., specific organism, severity, or clinical diagnosis) that are absent from the source term.   • Fits context: Classified as a Clinical Finding under “Abnormal finding on evaluation procedure,” exactly matching the laboratory nature of the source term.  No other target concept meets all these criteria; others are either for female genital organs, different test modalities (cytology, histology, immunology), different specimen sites (urine, CSF), or represent disorders rather than laboratory findings. Hence, concept 4171911 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Surgical operation with formation of external stoma as the cause of abnormal reaction of the patient, or of later complication, without mention of misadventure at the time of the procedure
cleaned_term: Abnormal reaction or later complication due to surgical operation with formation of external stoma
mapped_rationale: The source term describes any unintended pathological condition—whether immediate (“abnormal reaction”) or delayed (“later complication”)—that arises from a surgical procedure in which an external stoma is constructed. Its examples (infection, bleeding, prolapse, stenosis, leakage, fistula, etc.) are exactly the spectrum of problems that can occur at a stoma site.  Concept 4123283 “Disorder of stoma” is defined as “any pathological condition affecting a surgically constructed stoma, including infectious, inflammatory, mechanical, ischemic, or dermatologic problems such as infection, bleeding, prolapse, retraction, stenosis, leakage, fistula…” This encompasses the full range of postoperative and late complications of any external stoma (colostomy, ileostomy, urostomy, tracheostomy, etc.)  Specificity check (Rule 1): The target concept is not broader than the source; it is limited to disorders/complications of surgically formed stomas, matching the source’s focus on complications of external stoma formation.  Generality check (Rule 2): The target is not narrower; it does not restrict the type of stoma or the timing (acute vs. late) and therefore fully covers the source’s breadth.  Context validation (Rule 3): The SNOMED hierarchy places this concept under “Stoma finding/Disease,” confirming it is a clinical condition related to stoma pathology, in line with the source term.  Because 4123283 captures exactly the clinical scenario described—any abnormal reaction or late complication of a surgically created external stoma—it is an exact clinical equivalent.

The source term denotes any deviation from the normal cardiac rate, rhythm, or conduction, explicitly mentioning tachycardia, bradycardia, irregular rhythms, ectopic beats and conduction blocks.   SNOMED concept 4262562 “Abnormal heart beat” is defined as “a clinical finding in which individual cardiac contractions exhibit an atypical rate, rhythm, or pattern, reflecting an underlying disturbance in impulse generation or conduction.” This captures exactly the same breadth of abnormalities (rate, rhythm and conduction) described in the source.  • Specificity preserved (Rule 1): The target is neither broader (it excludes normal rhythm) nor narrower (it does not restrict the abnormality to a particular subtype, severity, age-group, or etiology).   • No over-specification (Rule 2): It adds no extra detail beyond what is present in the source.   • Context appropriate (Rule 3): It sits under “Finding of regularity of heart rhythm,” matching the clinical-finding nature of the source phrase “abnormalities.”    Other candidates such as “Cardiac arrhythmia” represent a disease/disorder category rather than a generic clinical finding, while “Abnormal cardiac rate” or “Irregular heart beat” omit portions of the spectrum (e.g., conduction blocks). Therefore, 4262562 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Abscess of breast associated with pregnancy, unspecified trimester
target_concept_name_b: Abscess of breast, associated with childbirth
cleaned_term: Abscess of breast associated with pregnancy
mapped_concept_name: Obstetric breast abscess with antenatal complication
mapped_rationale: The source term describes a breast abscess that develops specifically during pregnancy (i.e., in the antenatal period).   Concept 78218 is defined as “a suppurative collection within the breast that arises as a complication during the antenatal period of pregnancy.” This exactly mirrors the clinical scenario in the source term:  • Specificity maintained: Both the source and the target restrict the abscess to the breast and to the timeframe of pregnancy/antenatal period.   • Not over-specific: The target concept does not add details (e.g., laterality, lactation, postpartum status) that are absent from the source term.   • Context validated: It is classified under “Obstetric breast abscess,” indicating pregnancy-related etiology, which is clinically appropriate.  All other candidate concepts are either broader (e.g., “Obstetric breast abscess” includes postpartum cases) or refer to postpartum/lactational abscesses, nipple-specific abscesses, or general pregnancy findings, violating rule 1 or rule 2. Therefore, concept 78218 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Abscess of bursa, right ankle and foot
cleaned_term: Abscess of bursa, right ankle and foot
mapped_rationale: The source term specifies all three of the following elements:  1. An abscess of a synovial bursa (pathology = bursal abscess).   2. Laterality = right side.   3. Location encompasses both the ankle and the foot region ("right ankle and foot" is an ICD-10 wording that means the abscess may be in any bursa situated around the right ankle or the right foot).  None of the candidate concepts simultaneously satisfy all three requirements:  • Concepts 37207739 (“Abscess of bursa of right ankle”) and 37208271 (“Abscess of bursa of right foot”) include the correct pathology and laterality but cover only one of the two anatomical sites; each is therefore more specific than (i.e., a subtype of) the source term and violates Rule 2 (Do not over-specify).  • Concepts such as 4001625 (“Abscess of bursa of ankle”) and 4001122 (“Abscess of bursa of foot”) lack the required right-side laterality and thus are broader than the source term, violating Rule 1 (Do not broaden).  • Generic concepts like 4049120 (“Abscess of bursa”) are even broader, lacking both laterality and site specificity, also violating Rule 1.  • Concepts involving tendon sheath, skin, or generic ankle/foot abscesses involve different tissues or broader categories and fail Rule 3 (incorrect clinical context).  Because no listed concept exactly matches the combination of pathology, laterality, and anatomical scope of the source term, there is no exact clinical equivalent among the targets.

target_concept_name: Accident caused by power transmission machinery
mapped_concept_name: Accident caused by power transmission machinery
mapped_rationale: • Clinical meaning: Both the source term and SNOMED concept describe injury events produced by the moving parts that transmit mechanical power (belts, chains, gears, pulleys, shafts, etc.).   • Specificity: The target concept is neither broader nor narrower than the source. It covers exactly the same class of machinery (power-transmission equipment) and the same circumstance (an accident causing injury).   • Context validation: The concept sits under “Accident caused by machinery” and has children for each individual transmission component, confirming that it represents the generic group of transmission-machinery accidents, not a different or more specific subset.   • No added or missing qualifiers: There are no extra details (e.g., laterality, injury type, setting) that would over-specify the term, and no essential detail from the source term is lost.  Therefore, concept 439456 is an exact clinical equivalent.

The source term describes the psychocutaneous acne variant in which patients compulsively pick or scratch otherwise mild acne lesions, producing conspicuous excoriations and scars. Target concept 4004094 “Excoriated acne” has an identical definition (“A form of acne vulgaris in which patients repeatedly scratch or squeeze minor lesions, resulting in conspicuous erosions, crusts and scars…”) and lists the French synonym “Acne excoriee des jeunes filles,” which is the original French name for “Acné excoriée.”    • Specificity preserved (Rule 1): The target is neither broader (e.g., “Acne”) nor narrower; it captures exactly the excoriated subtype.   • No over-specification (Rule 2): The target adds no extra qualifiers (e.g., laterality, severity) that are absent from the source.   • Context appropriate (Rule 3): It is a disorder-level skin condition under Acne and Excoriation of skin, matching the psychocutaneous nature described.    Therefore, concept 4004094 is the exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Acquired absence of bilateral breasts and nipples
cleaned_term: Acquired absence of bilateral breasts and nipples
mapped_rationale: The source term requires ALL of the following details to be preserved:   1. Acquired (post-natal) loss,   2. Complete absence of BOTH breasts,   3. Simultaneous absence of BOTH nipple–areolar complexes.  None of the target concepts meet all three requirements:  • 36716836 “Bilateral acquired absence of breast” satisfies ‘acquired’ and ‘bilateral’, but it does not specifically state loss of the nipple-areolar complexes. In clinical terminology bilateral loss of breast tissue can still occur with nipple preservation (e.g., nipple-sparing mastectomy), so this concept is more general than the source (violates Rule 1: Maintain Specificity).  • 36717483 “Acquired total absence of breast” may include nipple loss but is not explicitly bilateral, so it is also broader in scope than the source.  • All remaining concepts either:   – describe unilateral or partial breast absence,     – concern congenital rather than acquired absence, or     – pertain to entirely different organs.  Because no target concept preserves every key clinical detail (acquired + bilateral + breasts AND nipples), there is no exact clinical equivalent.

cleaned_term: Acquired absence of left breast and nipple

source_term: Acquired deformity of chest and rib
cleaned_term: Acquired deformity of chest and rib
mapped_rationale: The source term describes a post-natal structural abnormality involving both the chest and the ribs.  In anatomic terminology, the “chest wall” is the composite bony and cartilaginous cage that includes the ribs, sternum, costal cartilages and related structures.   • The target concept “Acquired deformity of chest wall” is defined as “Any distortion in shape … of the bony or cartilaginous thoracic cage (ribs, sternum, clavicles and costal cartilages) that develops after birth,” which explicitly contains the ribs and the rest of the chest wall.   • Therefore it completely covers the clinical content of the source term (acquired, post-natal; deformity; involving ribs and the remainder of the chest).   • It is neither broader nor narrower in a clinically meaningful way: it is not limited to a single rib (so it is not too specific), and it does not extend beyond the thoracic cage into unrelated regions (so it is not unduly broad).   • Other candidates are either too narrow (“Acquired deformity of rib” omits other chest-wall elements) or too broad (“Acquired deformity of thoracic structure” also includes scapula, spine, intrathoracic soft tissues).    Accordingly, concept 40487194 is the exact clinical equivalent of “Acquired deformity of chest and rib.”

The target concept 375736 carries the identical clinical phrase “Trachoma, active stage.” Its definition describes precisely the same inflammatory phase of trachoma—characterised by conjunctival follicles, papillary hypertrophy, mucopurulent discharge, early pannus, high infectivity and responsiveness to antibiotic therapy—that is given for the source term. Hence:   • Specificity preserved (Rule 1): It is not broader than “Active stage of trachoma”; it refers to exactly the same stage and no other.   • No over-specification (Rule 2): No additional details (e.g., eye laterality, severity modifiers) are added beyond what is present in the source.   • Context validated (Rule 3): It is a disorder under “Trachoma,” consistent with the source condition.  Therefore, concept 375736 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Acute erosion of stomach with haemorrhage
target_concept_name_b: Acute erosion of stomach with haemorrhage
cleaned_term: Acute erosion of stomach with haemorrhage
mapped_rationale: The source term describes 3 indispensable attributes:   1. Lesion type: a superficial gastric mucosal erosion (not an ulcer).   2. Temporality: acute onset.   3. Complication: hemorrhage.  Evaluation of the candidate concepts:  • 4231580 “Acute gastric ulcer with hemorrhage” – specifies an ulcer (full-thickness defect), not an erosion → more specific to a different pathology.   • 4143871 “Erosion of stomach with hemorrhage” – matches lesion type and hemorrhage, but omits the “acute” qualifier → broader than the source.   • 4087594 “Acute gastric mucosal erosion” – includes “acute” and “erosion” but lacks hemorrhage → broader than the source.   • All remaining concepts pertain to ulcers, other parts of the GI tract, additional complications (perforation, obstruction), chronic disease, or are purely morphologic terms; none simultaneously incorporate all three required attributes.  Because no target concept preserves every key clinical detail without adding or omitting information (Rules 1 and 2), an exact clinical equivalent is not present in the list.

source_term: Acute hepatitis C with hepatic coma
target_concept_name: Hepatic coma due to acute hepatitis C
cleaned_term: Acute hepatitis C with hepatic coma
mapped_concept_name: Hepatic coma due to acute hepatitis C
mapped_rationale: The source term describes a fulminant presentation of newly acquired (acute) hepatitis C that has progressed to grade IV hepatic encephalopathy (hepatic coma).   Concept 46270037 is defined as “Grade IV hepatic encephalopathy occurring as a consequence of severe, recent-onset hepatitis C virus infection that produces fulminant hepatic failure, resulting in deep coma…”.    This concept: • Includes the same etiologic agent (hepatitis C virus).   • Specifies that the infection is acute / recent-onset, satisfying the “acute” requirement.   • Explicitly states the presence of hepatic coma (grade IV encephalopathy).    Therefore it matches all key clinical details—stage (acute), causative disease (hepatitis C), and complication (hepatic coma)—without adding extra specificity or omitting any element, fulfilling Rules 1–3.

source_term: Acute on chronic systolic (congestive) heart failure
target_concept_name: Acute on chronic systolic heart failure
cleaned_term: Acute on chronic systolic (congestive) heart failure
mapped_concept_name: Acute on chronic systolic heart failure
mapped_rationale: The source term describes an acute decompensation superimposed on pre-existing systolic (reduced-ejection-fraction) congestive heart failure. Concept 40480602 has the exact same clinical scope:   • It is explicitly “acute on chronic,” capturing the superimposed acute episode on a chronic condition (timing/severity preserved – Rule 1).   • It specifies “systolic heart failure,” thereby maintaining the requirement of reduced ejection fraction and not adding diastolic or other subtypes (specificity preserved – Rule 1, no over-specification – Rule 2).   • The definition and parents (“Acute exacerbation of chronic heart failure; Chronic systolic heart failure; Acute systolic heart failure”) confirm that the concept represents acute decompensated congestive heart failure in a patient with chronic systolic dysfunction, matching the clinical presentation, prognosis, and treatment outlined in the source definition (context validated – Rule 3).    No other candidate is as precise: alternatives are either broader (e.g., “Acute exacerbation of chronic congestive heart failure,” which does not specify systolic dysfunction) or narrower/different (e.g., combined systolic and diastolic failure). Hence, 40480602 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Acute onset vascular dementia with other, mainly hallucinatory symptoms, severe
cleaned_term: Acute onset vascular dementia with hallucinatory symptoms, severe

mapped_rationale: The source term describes a sudden loss of right-ventricular pump function producing systemic venous congestion and low pulmonary flow—precisely the clinical picture of acute right-sided heart failure.   Concept 4233424 carries exactly the same clinical meaning:  • Same side and chamber: “right-sided / right ventricular.”   • Same time course: “acute / rapid-onset.”   • Same pathophysiology and precipitants (pulmonary embolism, RV infarction, acute pulmonary hypertension, postcardiac surgery) and the same therapeutic priorities (hemodynamic support, treat cause).    It is neither broader (it is limited to the right side and to acute presentations) nor more specific (it does not introduce extra qualifiers such as “congestive,” “on chronic,” or procedure-related variants). Therefore it satisfies Rules 1 and 2 and is the exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Adverse effects in the therapeutic use of aminoglycosides
cleaned_term: Adverse effects in the therapeutic use of aminoglycosides
mapped_rationale: The source term describes any harmful, unintended clinical manifestation that occurs during or after proper therapeutic administration of any aminoglycoside antibiotic.   Concept 4099883 “Aminoglycosides adverse reaction” is defined as harmful effects precipitated by administration of any aminoglycoside antibiotic, explicitly listing the same typical toxicities (renal tubular injury, ototoxicity, neuromuscular blockade, hypersensitivity).   • Specificity: It refers to the entire aminoglycoside class (not broader like all antibacterials, nor narrower like a single agent), preserving exactly the scope of the source term.   • Generality: It does not add extra detail (e.g., overdose, sequelae, specific organ toxicity) that would make it more specific than the source.   • Context: It is classified as an adverse drug reaction/disorder, matching the clinical context of “adverse effects” from therapeutic use.  Thus, it is an exact clinical equivalent according to rules 1–3.

source_term: Adverse effects in the therapeutic use of antiparkinsonism drugs
cleaned_term: Adverse effects in the therapeutic use of antiparkinsonism drugs
mapped_rationale: The source term describes any harmful, unintended reaction that occurs when antiparkinsonism medications (those used to treat Parkinson’s disease or related parkinsonian disorders) are taken at standard therapeutic doses. Concept 443602 “Adverse reaction to antiparkinsonism drug” from SNOMED CT has an identical clinical scope: it refers to undesirable effects arising from therapeutic administration of antiparkinsonism drugs (levodopa, dopamine agonists, anticholinergics, MAO-B inhibitors, amantadine, etc.), including the same representative manifestations (dyskinesias, motor fluctuations, neuro-psychiatric and autonomic disturbances).    • Specificity: The target concept is neither broader nor narrower; it covers adverse reactions to the entire antiparkinsonism drug class, exactly matching the source term’s level of detail (Rule 1).   • Generality: It does not introduce additional qualifiers (e.g., a particular subtype, laterality, severity) absent from the source (Rule 2).   • Context: The concept’s definition, parents (“Adverse reaction to drug”) and synonyms confirm it is appropriate for recording adverse therapeutic effects of antiparkinsonian agents (Rule 3).   • Non-essential wording differences (“effects” vs. “reaction”) are semantically equivalent (Rule 4).    Therefore, concept 443602 is an exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Adverse effects in the therapeutic use of mineralocorticoids
cleaned_term: Adverse effects in the therapeutic use of mineralocorticoids
mapped_rationale: • Rule 1 – Maintain specificity: The source term is limited to adverse (harmful, undesired) effects that occur during therapeutic administration of mineralocorticoid hormones or their analogues. Concept 4303811 is defined as “any harmful or undesired clinical effect attributable to exposure to a mineralocorticoid drug (e.g., fludrocortisone)”, explicitly listing the same typical manifestations (salt and water retention, hypertension, edema, hypokalemia, etc.). It is neither broader (does not include other drug classes) nor narrower (does not restrict to a single mineralocorticoid or a particular presentation).    • Rule 2 – Maintain generality: The target concept covers the entire class of mineralocorticoid drugs, just as the source term does. It does not introduce extra qualifiers such as overdose (“poisoning”) or specify a particular agent (e.g., fludrocortisone) or patient group.    • Rule 3 – Context validation: Vocabulary context places this concept under “Corticosteroids adverse reaction,” matching the pharmacologic category and confirming it is considered a drug-related adverse effect disorder, exactly the clinical scenario described in the source term.    Because the target concept fully retains the clinical scope and detail of the source term without adding or omitting relevant information, it is an exact clinical equivalent.

The source term describes unwanted clinical effects that arise when a patient is treated with levothyroxine (synthetic thyroxine sodium).   Concept 4162153, “Thyroxine adverse reaction,” is defined as “any deleterious clinical effect produced by therapeutic administration of thyroxine preparations, typically reflecting thyrotoxic symptoms … and managed by dose adjustment or discontinuation.” This definition matches the source term in every clinically relevant respect:  1. Same active drug: both refer to thyroxine/levothyroxine (the sodium salt is simply the pharmaceutical form of thyroxine).   2. Same nature of problem: an adverse reaction occurring at therapeutic (non-toxic) dosing, not overdose or allergy alone.   3. Same typical clinical picture and management (symptoms of iatrogenic thyrotoxicosis, dose reduction, symptomatic β-blockade).  The concept is not broader (it is specific to thyroxine, not all thyroid hormones) and not narrower (it does not add side details such as formulation, route, laterality, or allergy subtype). Therefore it preserves the exact level of specificity required (Rules 1 & 2) and fits the clinical context (Rule 3).  All other candidate concepts are either: • broader (e.g., “Adverse reaction to thyroid hormone”),   • unrelated drugs (e.g., antithyroid or corticosteroid reactions), or   • different clinical entities (e.g., “Levothyroxine poisoning” which denotes overdose, not therapeutic adverse reaction).  Hence concept 4162153 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Alcohol abuse with alcohol-induced psychotic disorder
cleaned_term: Alcohol abuse with alcohol-induced psychotic disorder

mapped_rationale: The source term explicitly requires BOTH of the following clinical elements at the same time:   1. Chronic alcohol dependence (physiologic dependence with tolerance and withdrawal risk).   2. Current episode of acute alcohol intoxication.  None of the candidate target concepts include both elements:  • 435243 “Alcohol dependence” – contains dependence but not intoxication (violates Rule 1: would broaden by omitting required intoxication component).   • 4104431 or 607208 “Alcohol intoxication / Acute alcohol intoxication” – contain intoxication but not dependence (also violates Rule 1).   • 36713086 “Alcohol induced disorder co-occurrent and due to alcohol dependence” – refers to a separate alcohol-induced medical or psychiatric disorder, not simple intoxication, so adds detail not present and still does not necessarily specify intoxication (violates Rules 1 and 3).   • All remaining concepts describe other substance dependencies, intoxications, withdrawal, delirium, or complications, none of which match the combined specification.  Because no target concept preserves all essential clinical details without adding or omitting information, there is no exact clinical equivalent in the provided list.

source_term: Alcohol use, unspecified with withdrawal delirium
mapped_rationale: The source term describes delirium tremens that arises after abrupt reduction or cessation of heavy alcohol use—an acute confusional state with autonomic hyperactivity, hallucinations, and seizure risk. The source term “Allergic purpura” historically refers to Henoch-Schönlein purpura, now officially termed “Immunoglobulin A vasculitis.”   • Clinical presentation: both are leukocytoclastic small-vessel vasculitides with palpable purpura on dependent skin, arthralgia/arthritis, colicky abdominal pain, and possible glomerulonephritis.   • Pathophysiology: both are immune-complex disorders driven by IgA deposition in vessel walls.   • Triggers and course: both are commonly post-infectious or drug-related and are usually self-limited, matching the target concept’s description.   • Terminology: the target concept lists synonyms “Henoch-Schoenlein purpura,” “Anaphylactoid purpura,” and explicitly “Allergic purpura,” confirming exact naming equivalence.    The concept is neither broader (it remains a specific IgA-mediated vasculitis) nor narrower (it does not add laterality, chronicity, or other details not present in the source). Therefore it satisfies Rules 1–3 and is the precise standard concept.

“Broken” in musculoskeletal terminology denotes a fracture. Concept 4059173 “Fracture of ankle” is defined as “a break in one or more of the bones forming the ankle joint complex…,” which is identical in anatomical location, pathological process (fracture), acuity, and scope (may be open or closed, any bone, any side).    • Rule 1 – Maintain Specificity: The target concept is not broader (it excludes other ankle injuries such as sprains) and not narrower (it does not restrict side, openness, number of malleoli, or etiology).   • Rule 2 – Maintain Generality: It is not over-specified; it matches the same level of detail as the source (“broken ankle” does not stipulate side, open/closed, or malleolar pattern).   • Rule 3 – Context validation: Its SNOMED hierarchy places it under “Injury of ankle” and “Fracture of lower limb,” fully consistent with an ankle fracture.    Therefore, concept 4059173 is an exact clinical equivalent to “Broken ankle.”

The source term describes an unruptured dilation of an intracranial (cerebral) artery.   • Location: Both the source and the target specify the lesion is on a cerebral artery (intracranial, circle of Willis branches).   • Rupture status: In SNOMED, “Aneurysm of cerebral artery” represents the morphologic abnormality itself; ruptured lesions are coded separately (e.g., “Ruptured cerebral aneurysm”). The absence of the word “ruptured” therefore implies an intact-wall (non-ruptured) aneurysm, matching the source term’s “nonruptured” qualifier.   • Specificity: The concept is not broader (it excludes ruptured aneurysms) and not narrower (it does not impose etiology, number, or specific arterial branch), so it preserves all clinical detail present in the source while adding none.   • Context: The definition given for the target concept aligns exactly with the clinical presentation, prognosis, and treatment considerations outlined in the source description (risk of enlargement, compression, potential future rupture).    Because the target concept matches the location and implicit non-ruptured status without adding or omitting clinically relevant detail, it is an exact clinical equivalent under rules 1-3.

Cause-restricted chondrolysis (post-traumatic, congenital) introduce extra specificity not present in the source (rule 2) and still omit the forearm location.   18-22 – Describe other forearm conditions (contracture, osteitis, periostitis, infection, epiphyseal arrest) unrelated to chondrolysis. Therefore, concept 135214 is an exact clinical equivalent to the source term.

The source term “Classical hydatidiform mole” is synonym-ous with “complete hydatidiform mole.” Both describe an abnormal pregnancy in which:  • All chorionic villi are hydropic with diffuse trophoblastic proliferation.   • No embryo/fetal tissue is present.   • The karyotype is diploid and entirely paternal (androgenetic).   • β-hCG levels are markedly elevated.   • There is an increased risk of progression to invasive mole or choriocarcinoma.  Target concept 4129710 “Complete hydatidiform mole” includes exactly these clinical, pathologic, and prognostic features in its definition. It is neither broader (does not include partial moles) nor narrower (does not add qualifiers such as malignancy, location, or behavior beyond what is intrinsic to a complete mole), satisfying Rules 1 and 2. It is also presented as a Disorder in SNOMED, matching the clinical condition context of the source term (Rule 3). Therefore, it is an exact clinical equivalent.

Synonyms such as “Clubbed fingers” are identical in meaning to “Clubbing of fingers.”    All key clinical details (bulbous distal phalanges, nail curvature change, typical associations) are preserved, making concept 134746 an exact clinical equivalent.  # Match: 134746

The source term describes an inherited disorder of neuromuscular transmission that 1) is present from birth or early childhood, 2) produces fatigable skeletal-muscle weakness, 3) is caused by germline mutations affecting acetylcholine synthesis, release, breakdown or receptor function, 4) lacks circulating autoimmune antibodies, and 5) is treated with agents such as acetylcholinesterase inhibitors, 3,4-diaminopyridine, ephedrine or β-agonists depending on the molecular defect.    Concept 4046356 “Congenital myasthenic syndrome” matches all of these attributes exactly: it is an autosomal recessive/dominant neuromuscular-junction disorder beginning in the neonatal period or childhood, caused by mutations in presynaptic, synaptic or postsynaptic genes, produces lifelong fatigable weakness without autoimmune antibodies, and has identical treatment options.    • Specificity: It is neither broader nor narrower than the source—both denote the whole group of congenital/developmental hereditary myasthenias (Rule 1 & 2).   • Context: The vocabulary, synonyms (“Congenital myasthenia”), parents (“Genetically determined myasthenia”), and listed children (specific CMS subtypes) all confirm the same clinical concept (Rule 3).   • Non-essential wording differences (“developmental” vs. implicit lifelong course) are ignorable (Rule 4).  No other target concept satisfies all criteria without being overly broad (“Genetically determined myasthenia”) or overly specific (e.g., “Familial infantile myasthenia”, “End-plate acetylcholinesterase deficiency”). Therefore, concept 4046356 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

The target concept 4080755 “Cutaneous chromoblastomycosis”: • Specifies the same anatomic location (skin and subcutaneous tissue) as the source term (“cutaneous”).   • Describes the identical etiologic agents (dematiaceous fungi, most often Fonsecaea or Cladophialophora).   • Lists the same clinical features (slowly enlarging verrucous/warty or nodular plaques, potential for secondary infection, lymphedema, malignant transformation) and the same need for prolonged systemic antifungal therapy ± surgery or cryotherapy.    Thus it preserves every key clinical detail (Rule 1: maintains specificity) without adding extra qualifiers or narrowing to a particular subtype (Rule 2: no over-specification).   Given the complete semantic equivalence, 4080755 is an exact clinical match; no other candidate is as appropriate.

1. Clinical equivalence: The source term is defined as “a mental health condition in which regulation of affect is persistently disturbed….”  Concept 444100 is defined as “a class of psychiatric illnesses in which the primary symptomatology involves pathological elevation, depression, or fluctuation of mood.”  Dysregulation of affect/emotion is exactly what is meant by a mood (affective) disorder, so the clinical content matches.  2. Terminological evidence:  The target concept carries the exact synonyms “Affective disorder” and “Disorder of affect,” terms that are historically interchangeable with “Emotional disorder.”  Thus, it is the standard SNOMED term used for this clinical idea.  3. Specificity check (Rule 1 & 2):      • Not broader: Mood disorder is limited to persistent pathological disturbances of mood/affect; it does not include unrelated psychiatric conditions (e.g., psychotic disorders without affective disturbance).      • Not narrower: The source term does not indicate a particular subtype (e.g., depressive vs. bipolar), age group, or etiology.  Concept 444100 likewise represents the whole category, not a specific subtype, so it is not over-specific.  4. Context validation:  It is classified as a “Disorder” in the Condition domain, matching the source term’s nature as a mental health disorder.  Because concept 444100 preserves all essential clinical details without adding or omitting relevant information, it is an exact standard equivalent for “Emotional disorder.”

source_term: Encephalopathy in endocrine and metabolic disorders classified elsewhere (machine translation)
cleaned_term: Encephalopathy in endocrine and metabolic disorders classified elsewhere (machine translation)
mapped_rationale: The source term describes a diffuse, non-traumatic encephalopathy that is secondary to systemic endocrine or metabolic disturbances such as thyroid storm, adrenal crisis, hypo-/hyper-glycemia, electrolyte imbalance, hepatic or uremic failure, and that reverses when the underlying disturbance is corrected. Other candidates are unsuitable:   – “Toxic metabolic encephalopathy” (43021132) is broader, adding exogenous toxin etiologies not stated in the source (violates Rule 1).   – “Disorder of brain” (372887) is far too general (violates Rule 1).   – All remaining concepts describe different conditions (neuropathy, myopathy, etc.) and do not represent encephalopathy (violates Rule 3).  Therefore, concept 372892 is the single standard concept that is an exact clinical equivalent of the source term.

“Hepato-lenticular degeneration” is the historical eponym for the autosomal-recessive ATP7B-related copper transport defect that produces toxic copper accumulation in the liver and lenticular (basal ganglia) nuclei, manifesting with chronic hepatitis/cirrhosis, neuro-psychiatric signs, Kayser-Fleischer rings, low ceruloplasmin, and requiring lifelong copper-chelating therapy or liver transplantation.    Concept 4229262 “Wilson's disease” is defined as the identical ATP7B-mediated disorder with the same pathophysiology, clinical features and treatment. Its synonym list explicitly contains “Hepatolenticular degeneration” and “Progressive lenticular degeneration,” confirming semantic equivalence.    It is neither broader (it is not a generic copper-metabolism disorder) nor narrower (it is not restricted to a particular clinical subtype of Wilson disease). Therefore it preserves exactly the same level of specificity as the source term, satisfying Rules 1 and 2.   All contextual metadata (parents: “Disorder of copper metabolism,” “Degenerative brain disorder,” etc.) align with the source description, fulfilling Rule 3.    Hence concept 4229262 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

Thus Rule 1 and Rule 2 are satisfied.   • Vocabulary context: Synonyms include “Neuroendocrine tumor,” which is the preferred modern synonym for carcinoid, and its parents/children show the expected organ-specific malignant carcinoid subtypes, confirming semantic appropriateness (Rule 3). The source term “Malingerer” describes “an individual who deliberately feigns, exaggerates, or fabricates physical or psychological symptoms to obtain external rewards.”   SNOMED concept 4051630 “Malingering (finding)” is defined as “intentional fabrication or gross exaggeration of physical or mental symptoms motivated by external incentives (e.g., financial compensation, avoiding duty, obtaining drugs).”  Why this is an exact clinical equivalent:  1. Same phenomenon: Both the source term and the target concept denote deliberate feigning of illness for external gain.   2. Person-level finding: In clinical coding, the finding of “malingering” is applied to a patient, meaning “the patient is a malingerer.” Thus the concept captures the attribute of the individual, satisfying the semantic intent of “malingerer.”   3. Specificity preserved: No additional qualifiers (e.g., type, severity, context) are introduced, and no essential detail from the source term is lost.   4. Not over- or under-specific: The concept is neither broader (it does not include unrelated behaviors) nor narrower (it does not restrict to a particular context such as military service or legal settings).   5. Vocabulary context: Classified under “Social problem not due to a mental disorder,” matching the standard nosological placement of malingering.  Other candidates (e.g., “Feigning of symptoms,” “Factitious disorder…,” “Pseudologia fantastica”) either omit the requirement for external incentives, represent related but distinct disorders, or describe different behaviors. Therefore, concept 4051630 is the only precise match.

The source term describes a person who “intentionally fabricates, exaggerates, or feigns physical or psychological symptoms for clearly recognizable external incentives,” i.e., the classic definition of malingering.   Target concept 4051630 “Malingering” is defined as “the conscious and intentional production or exaggeration of symptoms or functional impairments for external gain, without underlying illness explaining the complaints.”    1. Specificity preserved – Both the source term and the target concept include:      • deliberate, conscious fabrication or exaggeration of symptoms      • presence of recognizable external incentives/gain      • absence of true underlying illness      No key clinical element in the source term is lost or omitted.  2. No over-specification – The target concept does not introduce additional qualifiers (e.g., type of symptom, setting, or severity) that are absent from the source term.  3. Context validity – The SNOMED concept is a “Clinical Finding” under “Social problem not due to a mental disorder,” exactly matching the observational nature of labeling someone a malingerer.  Hence concept 4051630 “Malingering” is an exact clinical equivalent; no other candidate satisfies the match rules as precisely.

“Plasma cell sarcoma” is defined as a solitary malignant mass of monoclonal plasma cells that may arise either in bone (osseous) or soft tissue and that can precede or progress to multiple myeloma.    Concept 4216139 “Plasmacytoma” is described as “a localized clonal proliferation of malignant plasma cells forming a single bone lesion or soft-tissue mass; it lacks the diffuse marrow involvement of multiple myeloma but can progress to systemic disease.”   This captures every key element of the source term:   • Cell type: monoclonal plasma cells.   • Nature: malignant neoplasm.   • Presentation: solitary/localized tumor (bone or soft tissue).   • Relationship to myeloma: potential progression to multiple myeloma.    The concept is neither broader (it is confined to solitary lesions, not all plasma-cell neoplasms) nor narrower (it allows both osseous and extramedullary locations). Therefore it is an exact clinical equivalent, satisfying rules 1–3.

Polydipsia is clinically defined as a symptom of persistently excessive thirst that drives the patient to drink abnormally large amounts of fluid. Synonymy: In clinical usage, “excessive thirst” and “polydipsia” are accepted synonyms. All other candidate concepts are either broader (e.g., “Disturbance in content of thought”), different phenomena (e.g., “Poverty of speech”), or unrelated to mental-state findings (e.g., socioeconomic poverty). • Specificity preserved – The target concept explicitly attributes the priapism to pharmacologic agents (“caused by drug”), matching the “drug-induced” qualifier in the source term.   • No over- or under-specification – It does not introduce additional details (e.g., trauma, sickle-cell, congenital) that are absent from the source, nor is it broader (plain “Priapism”).   • Clinical equivalence – Definitions for both source and target describe a prolonged penile erection lasting >4 h precipitated by medications, typically ischemic and requiring emergency management with aspiration, intracavernosal sympathomimetics and possible surgical shunting.   • Context validation – The target is a SNOMED disorder under the parent “Priapism,” fully appropriate for a condition description. Because the target concept fully preserves the meaning and scope of the source term without expanding or omitting any clinically relevant detail, it is an exact clinical equivalent.

• Clinical content: Both the source term and the SNOMED concept describe a neoplasm whose cells are demonstrably positive for progesterone receptors.   • Specificity: The concept explicitly includes “positive,” preserving the key qualifier of the source term. It does not add any extra details about tumor site, stage, grade, or method, so it is neither broader nor more specific than the source term (Rules 1 & 2).   • Context: Although the concept is classified under “Disorder,” its definition and synonyms (“Progesterone receptor positive tumour”) clearly refer to the same laboratory/pathology finding that the source term conveys—that the tumor is hormone-responsive owing to PR expression.   No other candidate concept specifies positivity (many are generic “presence” observables or are site-specific, making them either broader or over-specified). The source term describes the clinical situation in which a patient with multiple sclerosis shows “ongoing, irreversible worsening of neurological impairment and accumulation of disability … independently of or in addition to acute relapses.”   The SNOMED concept 37311816 “Progressive multiple sclerosis” is defined as an MS phenotype “characterized from onset by a steady increase in neurologic disability, with or without super-imposed relapses.”    Why this is an exact clinical equivalent:   • Both terms capture the same key idea—persistent, irreversible neurologic deterioration in MS that is not confined to discrete relapses.   • The target concept is not broader: it is still confined to multiple sclerosis and specifically to its progressive course.   • The target is not more specific than required: it represents the umbrella category of progressive MS (encompassing primary and secondary progressive forms) without adding extra qualifiers (e.g., laterality, severity stage) that the source term does not specify.   • Vocabulary context confirms it is a disorder concept under “Multiple sclerosis” and “Progression of disease,” matching the source’s nature as a disease state rather than a management plan, staging measurement, or unrelated condition.  Therefore, 37311816 “Progressive multiple sclerosis” is the single standard concept that fully preserves the clinical meaning of “Progression of multiple sclerosis.”

The source term describes septic (pyogenic) arthritis confined to joints of the upper arm, which include both the glenohumeral (shoulder) and the elbow joints. A correct match therefore must:   • Specify that the arthritis is septic/pyogenic (infection by pyogenic bacteria).   • Restrict the anatomic location to the upper-arm region as a whole (i.e., must not be limited only to the shoulder or only to the elbow, nor extend to other body sites).    Evaluation of available target concepts:   1. Elbow pyogenic arthritis (ID 4346971) – too specific; covers only the elbow, omitting the shoulder (Rule 2 violation).   2. Pyogenic arthritis of shoulder region (ID 81099) or Pyogenic bacterial arthritis of shoulder (ID 759808) – likewise too specific; limited to the shoulder (Rule 2 violation).   3. Suppurative arthritis, Pyogenic bacterial arthritis, Infective arthritis, Bacterial arthritis, etc. – too broad; they permit any joint throughout the body and therefore lose the upper-arm restriction (Rule 1 violation).   4. Disorder of upper arm – neither specifies infection nor arthritis (fails Rule 3).   5. Organism-specific septic arthritis concepts (staphylococcal, pneumococcal, streptococcal) – both too broad in anatomy and over-specified in etiology compared with the source (Rules 1 and 2).    No target concept exactly captures “pyogenic/septic arthritis of the upper-arm region” encompassing either shoulder or elbow without adding or losing clinical detail. Accordingly, no exact clinical equivalent exists among the provided candidates.

The defining feature of the source term is that the rectal fistula is SIMPLE—i.e., a single, low-lying, non-branching tract that does not cross a major portion of the external sphincter. Procedure concepts (e.g., “Fistulectomy of rectum,” “Repair of rectal fistula”) describe treatment, not the disorder itself, so they are semantically inappropriate (Rule 3).  4. It preserves all key clinical details without adding unwarranted specificity (Rule 2) and is not broader than the source (it is limited to infectious cases, unlike general “tenosynovitis”) (Rule 1). Vocabulary context shows it sits under “Musculoskeletal infective disorder” and “Tendon sheath disorder,” fully appropriate for an infective tenosynovitis (Rule 3). Therefore, it is an exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Other specific joint derangements, not elsewhere classified, forearm
mapped_rationale: The source term describes a mechanical derangement of any joint belonging to the forearm region, explicitly including both the proximal and distal radioulnar joints as well as the radiocarpal (wrist) joint. An exact clinical equivalent must therefore:   • be a derangement (i.e., a mechanical intra-articular lesion)   • apply to all joints of the forearm region (not limited to only wrist or only one side)   • avoid introducing extra qualifiers (e.g., laterality) or omitting part of the region.  Review of the targets:  1. Derangement of joint of wrist region (ID 1076213) and its laterality-specific children restrict the pathology to the wrist region (radiocarpal/mid-carpal/distal radioulnar). They omit the proximal radioulnar joint and therefore are more specific than the source (Rule 2 violation).  2. Derangement of radiocarpal joint (ID 1077496) and its laterality-specific descendants are even narrower, covering only one particular joint (over-specification).  3. Joint derangement (ID 78228) is too broad because it can apply to any joint in the body, not specifically the forearm (Rule 1 violation).  4. Disorder of forearm (ID 136779) and other “disorder” concepts are over-broad and encompass many conditions besides mechanical derangement (Rule 1).  5. Concepts describing contracture, instability, pain, or general arthropathy are different clinical entities, not equivalent to derangement.  No target concept preserves exactly the same scope and specificity as “Joint derangement, forearm.” Consequently, an exact standard concept match is not present among the provided candidates.

source_term: Other meniscus derangements, Medial collateral ligament or Other and unspecified medial meniscus

Concept 77066 “Derangement of medial meniscus” has the same anatomic focus (medial meniscus), the same pathologic process (tear, displacement, degenerative deformation), and the same clinical manifestations (pain, effusion, clicking/locking, impaired stability).    • Rule 1 – Maintain Specificity: 77066 is not broader than the source because it is limited to the medial meniscus; more general concepts such as “Derangement of meniscus” would include lateral meniscus as well and are therefore too broad.   • Rule 2 – Maintain Generality: 77066 is not more specific than the source; it does not add laterality (right/left), horn location (anterior/posterior), chronicity, or traumatic etiology that the source does not specify.   • Rule 3 – Context validation: The synonyms, parents (“Derangement of meniscus”), and definition provided for 77066 align exactly with the clinical scenario described for “Medial meniscus derangement.”  All key clinical details correspond, and no extraneous details are introduced, making 77066 an exact clinical equivalent.

The source term describes an infectious/inflammatory bone marrow process that is present “at more than one skeletal location.”   Concept 134137 (Osteomyelitis of multiple sites) is defined as “active infection of the bone and marrow occurring in two or more distinct anatomic locations,” which mirrors exactly the clinical meaning of the source term.    • Specificity preserved (Rule 1): The target explicitly requires involvement of “two or more” bones, just as the source does; it is not a broader single-site osteomyelitis.   • Not over-specified (Rule 2): The target does not add extra qualifiers such as “acute,” “chronic,” “hematogenous,” or a particular organism/site, so it does not narrow the meaning beyond what is stated in the source.   • Context validated (Rule 3): It is classified under “Osteomyelitis” within SNOMED, with children for acute and chronic forms, confirming it is the generic multifocal osteomyelitis disorder.  No other candidate meets these criteria—options that specify acute or chronic forms are more specific, and plain “Osteomyelitis” is too general. Therefore concept 134137 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

source_term: Other osteoporosis with pathological fracture, other
mapped_rationale: The source term describes a clinical situation in which osteoporosis has progressed to the point of producing a pathological (fragility) fracture.  Concept 40480160 “Osteoporotic fracture” is defined as “a bone break that occurs in tissue weakened by osteoporosis, typically precipitated by low-energy or no traumatic force because of reduced bone mineral density and compromised structure.”   • Specificity preserved (Rule 1): The target explicitly links the fracture to underlying osteoporosis, thereby capturing both the osteoporosis and the resulting pathological fracture. No anatomical site, laterality, or etiologic subtype is added or omitted, so no detail present in the source is lost or broadened.   • Not over-specified (Rule 2): The target does not introduce extra qualifiers (e.g., postmenopausal, drug-induced, vertebral, femoral, laterality) that are absent from the source.   • Context appropriate (Rule 3): SNOMED hierarchies show the concept under both “Osteoporosis” and “Stress/pathological fracture,” confirming identical clinical meaning.  No other listed concept represents the combined idea without adding or omitting key detail; therefore concept 40480160 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

The source term denotes a category of inflammatory skin diseases characterized by papules/plaques with scale and includes psoriasis, lichen planus, pityriasis rosea, seborrheic dermatitis, etc.   Target concept 4330878, “Papulosquamous dermatosis,” is defined as “any inflammatory skin condition that presents with scaly papules, plaques, or patches … encompasses entities such as psoriasis, lichen planus, pityriasis rosea, and related disorders.” This description is clinically identical to the source term:  • Specificity is preserved (Rule 1): the target concept is neither broader (it confines itself to papulosquamous conditions) nor narrower (it does not restrict to a particular subtype, site, or severity).   • No over-specification occurs (Rule 2): it introduces no extra qualifiers absent from the source.   • Context is appropriate (Rule 3): both are classed as inflammatory dermatoses; the examples listed overlap exactly.  Thus 4330878 is an exact clinical equivalent of “Papulosquamous disorders.”

target_concept_name: Respiratory distress syndrome in the newborn
mapped_rationale: The source term describes a nonspecific clinical syndrome of labored, ineffective breathing that presents in a newborn and may have many possible pulmonary, cardiac, infectious, or metabolic causes. The target concept 37161510 “Neonatal respiratory distress” is defined as “a clinical finding of abnormal breathing effort in a newborn—characterized by tachypnea >60 breaths/min, nasal flaring, grunting, retractions, or cyanosis—signifying compromised pulmonary function from a broad range of pathological processes.”    • Specificity: The target concept contains exactly the same essential clinical information—respiratory distress in a neonate—without adding details that are not in the source (Rule 2) and without omitting any key features (Rule 1).    • Generality: It is not limited to a particular etiology (e.g., surfactant deficiency) or a narrower time window (e.g., first 7 days), so it matches the breadth of “newborn,” which covers the first 28 days of life (Rule 2).    • Context validation: The concept sits under “Neonatal respiratory distress” and “Finding of neonate,” which is clinically appropriate to the source term’s description of a clinical syndrome rather than a specific disease entity (Rule 3).    Therefore, 37161510 “Neonatal respiratory distress” is the exact clinical equivalent of “Respiratory distress of newborn.”

source_term: Other specified types of schizophrenia, subchronic

All other candidate concepts are either:   • narrower subtypes of subchronic schizophrenia (e.g., subchronic paranoid, catatonic, residual), which would over-specify the source term, or   • different disorders altogether (e.g., schizotypal personality disorder, schizophreniform disorder), which would not be equivalent. source_term: Other forms of scoliosis, occipito-atlanto-axial region

Clinical equivalence: Both the source term and the target concept describe a structural lateral curvature of the spine that is NOT idiopathic or congenital but instead arises after birth because of another identifiable condition (e.g., neuromuscular disease, trauma, infection, tumor, surgery, metabolic bone disease). This is exactly the meaning of “secondary” in the source term and of “acquired” in the target concept’s definition.   2. Specificity maintained (Rule 1): The target concept is not broader than the source term; it is restricted to scoliosis (not all spinal curves) and explicitly excludes congenital and idiopathic forms, matching the source term’s exclusion of idiopathic cases.   3. No over-specification (Rule 2): The target concept does not add extra details about location, severity, age group, or etiology beyond the requirement that an identifiable cause exists, which is already implicit in the term “secondary scoliosis.”   4. Vocabulary context (Rule 3): SNOMED lists “Acquired scoliosis” under “Acquired curvature of spine” and alongside specific secondary etiologic subtypes (post-surgical, traumatic, thoracogenic, etc.), confirming it is the umbrella term for scoliosis secondary to another disorder or event. The source term describes “subjective complaints perceived by a patient that reflect disturbance in the function of the kidneys, ureters, bladder, or urethra,” listing examples such as dysuria, frequency, urgency, hesitancy, nocturia, incontinence, flank pain, and changes in urine appearance or volume.   Concept 74174 “Urinary symptoms” is defined as “subjective sensations or complaints reported by a patient that indicate altered urinary tract function—e.g., frequency, urgency, painful urination, nocturia, hesitancy, incontinence, or abnormal urine color or odor.”    This concept: • Captures the same scope (patient-reported symptoms of the urinary tract).   • Is neither broader (it is limited to symptoms, not all findings) nor narrower (it does not specify particular symptoms or etiologies).   • Shares identical clinical examples and anatomic coverage (kidneys, ureters, bladder, urethra).    Other candidates are either broader (“Urinary system finding,” includes signs, lab/imaging results) or pertain to disorders, procedures, or context changes, thus violating Rule 1 or Rule 2. Consequently, concept 74174 is the single exact clinical equivalent.

The source term requires BOTH of the following key clinical elements to be present simultaneously in the shoulder region:   • synovial-membrane inflammation (synovitis)   • tendon-sheath inflammation (tenosynovitis)  None of the candidate concepts preserves this full specificity:  1. 4118007 “Synovitis/tenosynovitis – shoulder” explicitly allows “involvement of the shoulder’s joint synovium OR the synovial tendon sheaths.” The “or” (and typical SNOMED use of a slash) means the concept covers cases with just synovitis, just tenosynovitis, or both together. Therefore it is broader than the source term, violating Rule 1 (Maintain Specificity).  2. 4035431 “Shoulder synovitis,” 37174220 “Synovitis of joint of right shoulder,” and 37174221 “Synovitis of joint of left shoulder” describe only synovitis and omit tenosynovitis, so they are narrower/incomplete.  3. 74728 “Synovitis and tenosynovitis” includes both conditions but at any body site, so it lacks the anatomic specificity to the shoulder.  All other listed concepts are either more general musculoskeletal disorders or pertain to other joints/conditions.  Because no target concept exactly matches the concurrent synovitis AND tenosynovitis limited to the shoulder, the correct outcome is “no_match.”

None of the candidate concepts satisfies all three requirements:  1. Urinary system finding (4024000) – includes normal findings as well as abnormal ones, therefore broader than the source (violates Rule 1).   2. Urinary bladder problem (4119470) – restricted to bladder only, missing kidneys & ureters (too narrow, violates Rule 2).   3. Disorder of the urinary system (75865) and Disorder of urinary tract (197331) – limited to diseases/disorders; they do not cover isolated symptoms such as frequency, urgency, pain (too narrow, violates Rule 2).   4. Urinary symptoms (74174) – covers only symptoms, omits established disorders (too narrow).   5. Genitourinary tract problem (4104308) – adds genital organs, therefore broader than the source (violates Rule 1).   6. All remaining concepts (e.g., urinary complication, impaired urinary system function, urinary tract obstruction, etc.) are either restricted to specific etiologies, complications, anatomical sub-sites or functional aspects, and thus are more specific than the source term (violating Rule 2).  Because no target concept exactly preserves the breadth of “urinary problems” without adding or omitting key clinical scope, there is no acceptable match.

• Clinical equivalence: The source term denotes any secondary condition that occurs as a result of primary varicella (chicken-pox) infection. The SNOMED concept “Chickenpox with complication” is defined as varicella infection that is “accompanied by one or more recognized local or systemic complications such as pneumonia, encephalitis, secondary bacterial skin infection, dehydration, or coagulopathy.” This definition captures exactly the same clinical idea—a chicken-pox case complicated by any of the listed adverse sequelae.   • Specificity preserved (Rule 1): The target concept retains all key elements—(a) primary varicella infection (chickenpox) and (b) the presence of one or more complications. It is not broader (it excludes uncomplicated chickenpox) and it is not narrower (it does not limit the type of complication).   • No over-specification (Rule 2): The source term does not specify which complication or any laterality, timing or severity details, and the target likewise leaves these open, so no additional clinical detail is introduced.   • Vocabulary context (Rule 3): The target concept sits under “Varicella” in SNOMED, confirming it is the recognized standard representation of complicated varicella infection.    Because it matches the clinical meaning exactly and respects the specificity/​generality requirements, 437791 “Chickenpox with complication” is the single best equivalent concept.
